04068nam a22004815i 9780226824789DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226824789  a(DE-B1597)626167  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.708692709732221 aKunzel, Regina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCriminal Intimacy :bPrison and the Uneven History of Modern American Sexuality /cRegina Kunzel. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b15 halftones, 2 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER ONE “An Architecture Adapted to Morals” -- tCHAPTER TWO “Every Prison Has Its Perverts” -- tCHAPTER THREE The Problem of Prison Sex in Mid- Twentieth- Century America -- tCHAPTER FOUR “The Deviants Are the Heterosexuals” -- tCHAPTER FIVE Rape, Race, and the Violent Prison -- tCHAPTER SIX “Lessons in Being Gay” -- tEPILOGUE -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSex is usually assumed to be a closely guarded secret of prison life. But it has long been the subject of intense scrutiny by both prison administrators and reformers—as well as a source of fascination and anxiety for the American public. Historically, sex behind bars has evoked radically different responses from professionals and the public alike. In Criminal Intimacy, Regina Kunzel tracks these varying interpretations and reveals their foundational influence on modern thinking about sexuality and identity. Historians have held the fusion of sexual desire and identity to be the defining marker of sexual modernity, but sex behind bars, often involving otherwise heterosexual prisoners, calls those assumptions into question. By exploring the sexual lives of prisoners and the sexual culture of prisons over the past two centuries—along with the impact of a range of issues, including race, class, and gender; sexual violence; prisoners’ rights activism; and the HIV epidemic—Kunzel discovers a world whose surprising plurality and mutability reveals the fissures and fault lines beneath modern sexuality itself. Drawing on a wide range of sources, including physicians, psychiatrists, sociologists, correctional administrators, journalists, and prisoners themselves—as well as depictions of prison life in popular culture—Kunzel argues for the importance of the prison to the history of sexuality and for the centrality of ideas about sex and sexuality to the modern prison. In the process, she deepens and complicates our understanding of sexuality in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPrison violencezUnited States. 0aPrisoners -- Sexual behavior -- United States. 0aPrisonersxSexual behaviorzUnited States. 0aRapezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226824789423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226824789/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles